metadata.name: The Rifting #46
metadata.description:
Generative artwork inspired by the effects of plate tectonics.
*click and wait for the music to fade in

There are four different rifts with 'Basin & Range' being the rarest.

The song is called 'The Rifting' originally released in 2018 by my alter ego 'Polynia'.
It was made by sampling some tape loops with an Akai S1000,
then playing the samples with a midikeyboard, finally recording an improv with a Tascam 4-track tape recorder.

metadata.name: Henge #342
metadata.description:
Henge is an exploration of circular megalithic structures of the prehistoric age. It is a work of historical fiction where these stone assemblies, achieved through herculean efforts of stacking, aligning, and balancing immense chiseled rocks, are reimagined within an alternate universe of algorithmic possibility. Historically, henges share a few qualities that inspired this project. First, they are places of gathering within a loose collection of stones to organize ceremony or worship under celestial alignments. They are also monolithic in their materiality and employ the most elemental techniques of megalithic, or large stone, construction. These particular types of henges, known as cromlechs, are circular spaces fit with purpose and ritual and in this sense, serve as precedents to the great human edifices; charging landscapes with meaning and presence through geometry and order. Finally, henges are a collective language of place-making shared across a range of cultures and ages, from the Mesolithic and Neolithic eras and across territories from modern-day Morocco, Portugal, Brazil, Germany, Scandinavia, to the well-known Stonehenge in Great Britain.

This project is deeply inspired by the timeless and universal narrative created through the thoughtful and deliberate placement of large rocks in a circle. It seems that when confronted with marking a place and communing with nature, human beings like to make circles out of stones. Among all the symbols of place making, the circle is the original and still remains the most universal. Through the use of code to portray these imperfect structures, Henge animates the history of these circles in all their roughness and seemingly endless variation.


--------

Created by Aranda\Lasch @ArandaLasch
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art
November 2022

[Interaction instructions]
'left' + 'right' arrow keys to change view
'i' saves a 2048x2048 PNG

[Info]
p5.js
Henge is optimized for Chrome, runs slowly on Firefox (the longer the wait, the more stones and/or grass are being generated)

metadata.name: Pobbles #129
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

 The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
 See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
 Alternative titles considered include Peggles, Plops, Blobbies, Floofs, Flintstones, Lardies, Plumps, Fats and Wet-Ones. 
 The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
 The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute. 
 They work well with toddlers.

 Collectors minting at the first auction tier receive a hand-crafted riso print of their pobble. Color variation between the file and the print will apply.

metadata.name: NOT A DOS DELIGHT #59
metadata.description:
"NOT A DOS DELIGHT" continues the legacy of the DOS DELIGHT series but with a modern twist, marked by the use of GPUs to create an illusion of Turkish paper marbling within the framework of retro computer aesthetics. This project designed to adapt to multiple aspect ratios; while maintaining determinism in features like color palettes and glyphs, it introduces subtle variations based on aspect ratio, ensuring a unique visual experience for each device.

Additionally, this project incorporates a fresh set of color palettes, distinct from the DOS DELIGHT series, drawing inspiration from the earthy hues found in Turkish marbling pigments.



Press 1 or 2 to export PNG.

For the optimal experience, I highly recommend engaging with "NOT A DOS DELIGHT" in fullscreen mode.

Murat Atimtay 2024 | @atimtay | www.atimtay.xyz
